00:00:02.140 --> 00:00:02.390
HAL BAILEY: Hello.

00:00:02.390 --> 00:00:04.300
My name's Hal Bailey.

00:00:04.300 --> 00:00:06.430
And I'm excited today.

00:00:06.430 --> 00:00:09.530
Kal and I met several years
ago in San Francisco.

00:00:09.530 --> 00:00:12.550
And I'm thrilled today to
have him here at Google.

00:00:12.550 --> 00:00:15.770
We've been talking about
this many years.

00:00:15.770 --> 00:00:18.860
Two of the things that I think
will resonate with most people

00:00:18.860 --> 00:00:23.630
here about Kal and his work are
one, he spends a lot of

00:00:23.630 --> 00:00:26.930
time and effort thinking about
the digital revolution.

00:00:26.930 --> 00:00:32.110
How the digital revolution is
changing both books, but also

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:33.550
art in general.

00:00:33.550 --> 00:00:37.960
And then also, he's been very
vocal about freedom of

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:40.980
expression, not just in the
United States and the United

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:44.000
Kingdom, where it's easy
to do that, but around

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:46.390
the world as well.

00:00:46.390 --> 00:00:47.960
So he's got lots of interesting

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:48.870
stories to tell us.

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:50.990
And I'll hand it over to him.

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:51.380
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: Great.

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:52.610
Thank you very much.

00:00:52.610 --> 00:00:53.920
Thank you, Hal.

00:00:53.920 --> 00:00:54.405
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:54.405 --> 00:00:55.375
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: Thanks,
everyone.

00:00:55.375 --> 00:00:55.860
Good to see you.

00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:56.280
Thank you.

00:00:56.280 --> 00:00:58.670
Thank you all for
coming today.

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:01.590
We're going to have some fun
today, partly because we're

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:02.920
going to be talking
a little bit about

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:04.760
the world of cartoons.

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:08.530
Political cartoons, which
innately should be fun.

00:01:08.530 --> 00:01:11.640
But also, I'm going to have a
little bit of fun because the

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:15.010
world of cartoons has been
shrinking of late.

00:01:15.010 --> 00:01:17.220
And what I mean is the
traditional cartoon that

00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:20.190
everyone knows about appears
in a newspaper.

00:01:20.190 --> 00:01:23.580
And soon, we may be saying,
what was the newspaper, as

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:28.420
everyone's attention moves to
the internet and absorbing

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:30.920
content on new devices.

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:32.840
And so, the numbers of political
cartoonists my

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:36.570
particular craft, has reduced,
I think in 25 years, from

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:40.950
about 200 in the
US to about 70.

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:43.260
And those numbers will
probably get smaller.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:44.890
And around the rest of the
world, there may be only

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:47.610
another hundred of us
that are doing this.

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:50.550
But today, we're going to change
all that, because in

00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:52.730
addition to me telling you a
little bit about the world of

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:56.160
cartoons that I reside in,
showing you some cartoons,

00:01:56.160 --> 00:02:00.670
doing a Q&amp;A, I'm also going to
draw some of my favorite

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:02.700
presidents that I've drawn
over the years.

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:05.980
But we're going to finish off
with a drawing lesson, where

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:08.940
I'm going to teach everybody
here how to draw Barack Obama.

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:09.720
OK?

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:12.610
So we're going to have like,
another 50 cartoonists by the

00:02:12.610 --> 00:02:13.160
end of the show.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.100
We hope that you guys
will practice.

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:18.700
And then we'll start a new
revolution starting today.

00:02:18.700 --> 00:02:20.720
So anyways, my world.

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:22.580
Editorial cartoonist.

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:25.570
I've been with "The Economist"
magazine for 35 years.

00:02:25.570 --> 00:02:28.500
And many of you have copies of
the book that just came out

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:31.080
about a month ago celebrating
that fact.

00:02:31.080 --> 00:02:34.130
And during my career, both for
"The Economist" and as

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:36.310
cartoonist is for "The Baltimore
Sun," where I had

00:02:36.310 --> 00:02:40.270
been, I've created over
8,000 cartoons.

00:02:40.270 --> 00:02:43.270
And I've created over
140 covers for

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:45.000
the magazine as well.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.020
And I wanted to give you guys
a little bit of insight into

00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:51.590
this very special type of
creativity that's involved in

00:02:51.590 --> 00:02:55.700
my craft, which requires both
the understanding of politics

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:59.270
and art, and done
on a deadline.

00:02:59.270 --> 00:03:01.920
But the thing that fascinates me
most about my craft is the

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:04.920
notion that you're dealing
with a certain kind of

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.360
technology.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:11.660
And the technology is pigment,
black pigment, on a white

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:13.200
piece of paper.

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:17.170
And when you see it appear in
front of you, it's completely

00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:21.530
individual, as individual as
each of our handwriting.

00:03:21.530 --> 00:03:26.800
Yet when it appears, suddenly
an image arrives.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:30.220
And everyone, no matter what
nationality, what language you

00:03:30.220 --> 00:03:32.930
speak, it will be universally
understood.

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:37.380
And there is no special
effects with this.

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:39.310
It's exactly what you see.

00:03:39.310 --> 00:03:41.630
There's something very human
and very tangible about the

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:42.930
act of drawing.

00:03:42.930 --> 00:03:46.400
But then, there's also something
about the power that

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:48.330
this line can create.

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:50.560
And we only have to think about
what happened to a group

00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:53.430
of Danish cartoonists just a few
years ago, when they drew

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:54.820
the Prophet Mohammad.

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:57.710
There were subsequent riots,
where hundreds

00:03:57.710 --> 00:03:58.960
of people were killed.

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:02.030
And it caused an international
outcry that still is an open

00:04:02.030 --> 00:04:03.190
wound today.

00:04:03.190 --> 00:04:05.770
So besides the fact that there's
a magic to this line,

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:08.080
there's also a power
to this line.

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:09.880
And I'm going to share with you
guys a little bit of the

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:11.420
inside of what it's like
to be a cartoonist.

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:12.950
Some of the skill
sets involved.

00:04:12.950 --> 00:04:15.370
Some of the background stories
that go into it, particularly

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:18.070
with my work with the
"Economist." And then, we'll

00:04:18.070 --> 00:04:20.440
have some fun doing some
drawing as well.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:21.459
So I thought I'd start--

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:22.910
I think it's a really important
thing when you're

00:04:22.910 --> 00:04:26.010
dealing with artists, it's
really important to look at

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:26.840
their early work.

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:29.520
You get some sort of sense
of where they come from.

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:31.940
And I'm going to show you this
cartoon, which is a seminal

00:04:31.940 --> 00:04:33.440
cartoons of mine.

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:36.790
Very important cartoon,
which I drew when I

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:38.970
was six years old.

00:04:38.970 --> 00:04:40.480
So now, this cartoon
is important.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:43.880
You might see it's got Abraham
Lincoln, "Gettysburg Address."

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:47.610
The reason why this cartoon is
so important is because this

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:51.020
cartoon inspired a feature
length motion picture starring

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:52.240
Daniel Day Lewis.

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:53.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:56.090
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: It's a
really important piece.

00:04:56.090 --> 00:04:57.360
But here's what's
cool about this.

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:01.440
At age six, everybody in
this room is drawing.

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:01.710
Right?

00:05:01.710 --> 00:05:03.340
We are all drawing.

00:05:03.340 --> 00:05:09.200
But somewhere between six and
13, most people drop off.

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:13.140
But we all have that in us, that
capacity to use lines to

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:16.030
dictate reality, to
translate reality.

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:17.830
It's all something
that we absorb,

00:05:17.830 --> 00:05:18.960
life through the lines.

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:21.430
And for me as a cartoonist, I'm
actually a professional

00:05:21.430 --> 00:05:22.260
six-year-old.

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:25.950
I kind of stayed with
this world of lines.

00:05:25.950 --> 00:05:29.910
So after graduating from
Harvard, I spent the next 11

00:05:29.910 --> 00:05:31.170
years living in the UK.

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:33.580
But I started as-- you're not
going to believe this--

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:36.190
a semi-professional
basketball player.

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:39.560
I was always taller back then.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:42.290
But I also, when the team is
having financial trouble, I

00:05:42.290 --> 00:05:45.170
went on the streets and started
drawing caricatures.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:47.630
And one of things when you're
a street artist, you get to

00:05:47.630 --> 00:05:51.910
see hundreds, if not thousands,
of faces.

00:05:51.910 --> 00:05:54.840
And you see people of all
different nationalities, all

00:05:54.840 --> 00:05:57.810
different shapes of heads,
all different ages and

00:05:57.810 --> 00:05:58.770
ethnicities.

00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:01.870
And you learn to deconstruct
and understand the

00:06:01.870 --> 00:06:03.730
complexities of the face.

00:06:03.730 --> 00:06:07.060
And the unfortunate thing,
though, is I was doing this to

00:06:07.060 --> 00:06:08.510
raise money.

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:10.860
And you can imagine the typical
caricaturists knock

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:11.560
something out, what?

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:13.600
In about three or
four minutes.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:15.660
And they put a tennis racquet
in the person's hand.

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:17.910
And they charge you whatever.

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:20.660
I was a terrible businessman,
because it used to take me a

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:23.180
half an hour or 45 minutes.

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:25.480
Because I wanted to capture
that person.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:28.170
The spirit of that individual.

00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:35.010
And I thought I was mad until
I read a famous quote by the

00:06:35.010 --> 00:06:38.480
Italian Renaissance painter,
Annibale Carracci, who said,

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:42.770
"A good caricature is more
true to life than reality

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:43.780
itself."

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:46.050
And it's this whole idea that
you can get to the soul of

00:06:46.050 --> 00:06:49.420
someone through a caricature
that's always inspired me.

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:52.440
So when I started working for
"The Economist" magazine back

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:56.140
in 1978, I now was no longer
drawing holidaymakers.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.350
I was now drawing
policymakers.

00:06:59.350 --> 00:07:01.970
And I was beginning to realize
and understand that the

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:06.920
cartoon, the caricature, was
not just a source of making

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:10.590
humorous assertions of people on
the streets, but now you're

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:13.440
taking on powerful people,
and you could

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:15.700
knock them down a notch.

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:18.180
And over this time, I've
drawn, wow, I've drawn

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:21.400
practically every major
politician over the years.

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:24.430
Certainly every American
president.

00:07:24.430 --> 00:07:26.240
And some of the American
presidents obviously offered

00:07:26.240 --> 00:07:28.760
more scope than others.

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:31.770
And I also found the caricatures
I was drawing were

00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:35.830
not simply representations of
the individuals, but they also

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:37.890
were telling stories.

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:40.050
This cartoon, for example,
appeared on the cover of the

00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:44.810
magazine "The Economist" not
long after Hurricane Katrina.

00:07:44.810 --> 00:07:48.890
But it was a metaphor of how
the Bush administration and

00:07:48.890 --> 00:07:51.610
their policies were also falling
apart in the same way

00:07:51.610 --> 00:07:52.640
that the country was.

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:56.090
And this is the only cover in
over 150 years "The Economist"

00:07:56.090 --> 00:07:59.230
ran with no words on it.

00:07:59.230 --> 00:08:01.320
And then, of course, caricatures
of individual

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:04.290
presidents who I've drawn
change over time.

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:05.640
Partly because we all
change over time.

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:07.520
But we've also seen how
Obama's has changed.

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:12.580
This is what he look like
in 2008 when he

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:13.600
ran the first time.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:16.660
You guys remember this guy,
the upward looking, the

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:19.020
optimistic, the hopeful
president?

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:23.570
And now, five years later, this
is what he looks like.

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:28.290
So the weight of the job, and
the gravity, and gravitas are

00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:31.380
kind of pulling its weight and
taking a toll on the face.

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:34.340
And so the drawing can
tell the story.

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:36.280
And the other thing that I
learned when I was watching

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:39.080
caricatures over time was it
was that people's shape of

00:08:39.080 --> 00:08:41.780
your head is the most
distinguishing characteristic

00:08:41.780 --> 00:08:42.659
that you have.

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:45.930
And so someone like John Kerry,
who's got a very long

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:49.250
face, made it good
for caricature.

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:51.760
And there's other guys, like
Joe Biden here, where the

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:55.790
smile gives a shape of its own
and creates the fundamental

00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:59.140
part of the recognition
of the face.

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:01.940
Now it's also a point that I
discovered over time that the

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:04.600
caricatures are not just
reflecting the important

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:07.890
people in the news, but they
can also be educational

00:09:07.890 --> 00:09:10.820
components, where they're
telling the readers who are

00:09:10.820 --> 00:09:14.490
the people, important people,
that you should know about.

00:09:14.490 --> 00:09:17.370
So someone like Nancy Pelosi,
who everyone wouldn't

00:09:17.370 --> 00:09:21.090
necessarily recognize if she
walked into the room, or

00:09:21.090 --> 00:09:22.880
Senator Reid of Nevada.

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:24.380
But these are important
people.

00:09:24.380 --> 00:09:26.750
If you put them in cartoons,
then people say, oh, maybe I

00:09:26.750 --> 00:09:29.600
should know who these
people are.

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:32.390
And then there's election
years, where we have new

00:09:32.390 --> 00:09:36.030
candidates coming along and
new challenges for the

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:39.170
cartoonist and the
caricaturist.

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:41.960
So I was in the UK, like I
said, for about 11 years.

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:46.520
And I hadn't been there for very
long before I realized

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:50.520
that as an American living
abroad, you are held

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:53.270
personally responsible for
everything that goes on in

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:54.910
this country.

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:58.900
So as a result, I became more
aware and more interested in

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:01.560
politics to try to figure
out what was going on.

00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:03.760
Partly because I learned that
every taxi driver in London

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:06.440
seemed to know more about
American politics than I did.

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:08.920
But I figured that I needed
to get my game up.

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:11.600
So I got this new interest in
politics, and I combined it

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:15.350
with my interest in cartoons
to become a political

00:10:15.350 --> 00:10:16.820
cartoonist.

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:20.070
Here, I was using caricature,
the skill set that I felt was

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:22.420
really one the most powerful
tools at the

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:24.870
disposal of a satirist.

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:27.530
But I was also using it
as a way to get your

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:30.550
interest into a cartoon.

00:10:30.550 --> 00:10:33.350
At that point, I deliver
a message.

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:35.970
And that makes the
good cartoon.

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:39.160
So because my job is not really
to make you laugh.

00:10:39.160 --> 00:10:44.270
My job is to make you think
using humor, using caricature,

00:10:44.270 --> 00:10:47.120
but using it as a vehicle
for a message.

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:50.850
And after that, hopefully,
making you challenge your

00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:54.720
thoughts and your ideas on the
important events of the day.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:56.350
So I will use caricatures.

00:10:56.350 --> 00:10:57.900
I thought caricatures
are great.

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:00.990
To quote another famous person,
another great British

00:11:00.990 --> 00:11:05.340
philosopher named Mary Poppins,
"A spoonful of sugar

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:09.830
helps the medicine go down." And
because we are animals and

00:11:09.830 --> 00:11:14.940
we are wired to look at faces,
whereby our eyes are scanners,

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:17.580
our brains are hard drives, and
all we do is every time we

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:20.000
look at the person, we're
eyeballing and we're assessing

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.490
them to see if they're friendly,
if we like them, are

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:25.120
they attractive, would I like
to go out with them, or

00:11:25.120 --> 00:11:25.840
whatever you're thinking.

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:30.840
Your brain is processing this
information instantaneously.

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:33.820
The caricature is the thing that
brings your eyeballs into

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:34.640
the cartoon.

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:37.520
And when you have them in there
for five or six seconds,

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:41.690
then you can deliver your
message at the same time.

00:11:41.690 --> 00:11:43.950
So now, I'm going to show you
some of the other tools in

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:47.220
addition to caricature that we
cartoonists use to get our

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:48.430
messages across.

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:50.730
So one of them, of course,
is symbols.

00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:53.790
The donkey and the elephant,
most famously in the United

00:11:53.790 --> 00:11:56.510
States, representative of
two different parties.

00:11:56.510 --> 00:11:58.440
Use them, of course,
in many cartoons.

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:01.870
This cartoon, for example,
I did in 2010 during the

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:02.950
mid-term elections.

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:06.490
Normally when the opposition
party gains an upper hand.

00:12:06.490 --> 00:12:08.380
We might expect to see
the same cartoon

00:12:08.380 --> 00:12:12.220
again in 2014, perhaps.

00:12:12.220 --> 00:12:13.900
Although I never recycle
cartoons.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:15.090
I want to make that clear.

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:15.300
All right.

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:19.260
So here's another famous symbol,
our friend Uncle Sam.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:24.960
So this cartoon I did after
a visit to Cuba in 1999.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:26.055
And there, you can
see Uncle Sam.

00:12:26.055 --> 00:12:27.030
He's got his microphone.

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:30.000
He's going, "People of Cuba!

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.530
Why stick with that dictator
idiot Castro when you can

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.820
freely elect your idiots
like we do?"

00:12:37.820 --> 00:12:40.190
And that was during the time
of the Monica Lewinsky

00:12:40.190 --> 00:12:41.970
nonsense and all that
stuff going on in

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:43.450
the background there.

00:12:43.450 --> 00:12:45.410
And then this cartoon about
Uncle Sam, one of my

00:12:45.410 --> 00:12:49.700
favorites, has Uncle Sam, "What
foreign enemies think

00:12:49.700 --> 00:12:54.440
Americans are looking for,
world control." "What

00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:56.370
Americans are really
looking for is,

00:12:56.370 --> 00:12:59.320
remote control." Right?

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:02.830
Again, our good friend
Uncle Sam.

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:05.560
Now, there's also, of course,
cartoons that are

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:08.640
not funny at all.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:13.210
When I live the job of an
editorial cartoonist, I live

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:15.700
within two polarities.

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:20.140
Editorial that is serious and
cartoonist that is funny.

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:23.520
And every day when I approach my
cartoons, I put myself on a

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:26.580
different part of that spectrum
according to the

00:13:26.580 --> 00:13:29.000
appropriateness of the
subject matter.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.070
And you guys all have to think
back to what it was like in

00:13:32.070 --> 00:13:37.580
the United States after 2001 and
the bombings in New York.

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:40.330
And any of you that've lived
abroad in countries where

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:43.330
they've had major terrorist
activity, is that there's not

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:45.640
a lot of humor to be found.

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:48.860
At those times, you have
to resort to other of

00:13:48.860 --> 00:13:51.030
your skill sets. .

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:54.080
This cartoon, for example, I
did a few days afterwards.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:55.976
And it's about terrorism.

00:13:55.976 --> 00:13:59.930
And it's about the beast of
terrorism that is both visible

00:13:59.930 --> 00:14:01.790
and invisible.

00:14:01.790 --> 00:14:04.330
A beast that you will not slay,
but one that must be

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:07.270
engaged just the same.

00:14:07.270 --> 00:14:10.570
But eventually over time, humor
does find its way back

00:14:10.570 --> 00:14:11.450
into the discussion.

00:14:11.450 --> 00:14:13.890
And actually, I think humor is
an important part of the

00:14:13.890 --> 00:14:15.330
healing process.

00:14:15.330 --> 00:14:18.360
And cartoonists often lead the
way as being some of the first

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:20.880
people to approach this
sort of thing.

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:23.770
And here's a cartoon I wanted
to show you that tells you a

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:26.810
little bit of a story about
what happened after 9/11.

00:14:26.810 --> 00:14:31.040
And in fact, in four panels, it
tells the entire story of

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:33.940
the decade long Iraq war.

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:37.640
So it starts off, we have Uncle
Sam, who thinks he sees

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:39.180
weapons of mass destruction.

00:14:39.180 --> 00:14:40.420
And he's going in.

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:42.900
And once he's in there,
where do they go?

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:44.110
They weren't here.

00:14:44.110 --> 00:14:46.430
And oh no, it's worse
than I thought.

00:14:46.430 --> 00:14:48.740
And then finally, oh,
there they are.

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:51.470
We finally found the weapons
of mass destruction.

00:14:51.470 --> 00:14:53.790
Maybe not exactly where
we thought they were.

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:54.630
AUDIENCE: And you're mooning
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:54.630 --> 00:14:55.850
KEVIN KALLAUGHER:
That's right.

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:59.060
So here, what's interesting too
is that note, this employs

00:14:59.060 --> 00:15:01.310
yet another tool for
the cartoonist.

00:15:01.310 --> 00:15:04.280
And that is narrative
storytelling.

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:05.820
Most of the cartoons you've
seen up to now

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:07.160
had a single panel.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:09.170
This one went over
several panels.

00:15:09.170 --> 00:15:10.410
You're telling a story.

00:15:10.410 --> 00:15:12.410
So being a cartoonist, you
also have to be a good

00:15:12.410 --> 00:15:13.300
storyteller.

00:15:13.300 --> 00:15:15.840
You have to be not only good
with pictures, but you have to

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.700
be good with timing.

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:20.360
This, by the way, I just wanted
to show you, is what

00:15:20.360 --> 00:15:22.270
Iraq looks like today.

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:25.410
This is much more of where we
stand, where Iraq is trying to

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:30.320
set off after the US is pulling
its hands away.

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:32.610
But it doesn't look like it's
going to move so steadily.

00:15:32.610 --> 00:15:35.360
I'll also add, for those of you
who've spent any time in

00:15:35.360 --> 00:15:37.830
England, you may know
in England--

00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:41.560
well here in the US we say, on
your marks, get set, go.

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:43.570
In England, they say,
ready, steady, go.

00:15:43.570 --> 00:15:45.190
And hence, that's why this
is ready, steady.

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:47.000
If this was done for "The
Baltimore Sun," it would've

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.150
said, on your marks, get set.

00:15:49.150 --> 00:15:50.670
And then everyone would have
known what happened.

00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:56.650
So we also do cartoons on a
whole array of subjects that

00:15:56.650 --> 00:15:59.610
are not necessarily specific to
individuals, where you have

00:15:59.610 --> 00:16:02.930
caricature, or symbols like
Uncle Sam, but they could be a

00:16:02.930 --> 00:16:06.100
much more grander process.

00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:07.940
This brings me around to the
point of saying that when

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:12.640
you're a cartoonist, the
world is our bailiwick.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:14.560
We have to cover everything.

00:16:14.560 --> 00:16:17.770
All the other writers and
columnists and newspapers,

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:20.000
they usually have certain
specific niches.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.260
As a cartoonist, I have to cover
everything, which means

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:26.790
keeping up with the news, which
is I think is the part

00:16:26.790 --> 00:16:28.430
of the my job that's
the hardest for

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:31.160
me to keep up with.

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:32.740
We have to do very sensitive
subjects

00:16:32.740 --> 00:16:33.920
as well, like religion.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:34.160
OK.

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:37.040
Here's a cartoon I wanted to
show you about religion.

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:37.940
It's set up in heaven.

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:40.860
And it says, "Hello, Lord
Almighty's office.

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:42.770
Michael be Archangel speaking.

00:16:42.770 --> 00:16:45.860
May I help you?"" And a voice
from offstage says, "Who is

00:16:45.860 --> 00:16:51.146
it?" "It's Pope John Paul II
on the line." "Again?"

00:16:51.146 --> 00:16:54.580
"He's worried about this
movement to ordain women as

00:16:54.580 --> 00:16:57.930
priests." "But I've already
told him what I think.

00:16:57.930 --> 00:17:00.510
Tell him I'm busy."
"I'm sorry.

00:17:00.510 --> 00:17:00.840
She's

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:03.770
busy right now." [LAUGHTER]

00:17:03.770 --> 00:17:06.030
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: So here, one
of the other elements of being

00:17:06.030 --> 00:17:08.880
a cartoonist is you've got
to be a good writer.

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:12.550
And here we have writing, and
timing, and panels all wrapped

00:17:12.550 --> 00:17:15.210
into one, because we had the
lead to the words to the last

00:17:15.210 --> 00:17:16.069
few seconds.

00:17:16.069 --> 00:17:17.730
Not giving away our hand.

00:17:17.730 --> 00:17:19.770
And so having all of that--
and this is what it looked

00:17:19.770 --> 00:17:21.460
like in the paper--

00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:26.890
having all of that work out in
a nice continuum that made it

00:17:26.890 --> 00:17:30.000
an effective joke.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.650
Now we also cover tough
subjects like guns.

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:32.950
All right.

00:17:32.950 --> 00:17:36.510
Now guns is a subject which
I've done many cartoons.

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:39.150
This is the cover of "The
Economist" that I did the week

00:17:39.150 --> 00:17:42.310
that Gabrielle Giffords got
shot down in Arizona.

00:17:42.310 --> 00:17:43.810
This is a very touchy subject.

00:17:43.810 --> 00:17:46.250
Every country and every
individual has

00:17:46.250 --> 00:17:47.750
certain touchy subjects.

00:17:47.750 --> 00:17:50.130
And here, of course, guns
is one of them.

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:51.285
So recently, I was in Beirut.

00:17:51.285 --> 00:17:54.140
And I was talking to a group
of Lebanese cartoonists,

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:55.260
showing my cartoons.

00:17:55.260 --> 00:17:57.930
And one of the cartoonists was
aware of the amount of gun

00:17:57.930 --> 00:17:58.650
cartoons I did.

00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:03.020
And he says, you've got to tell
me, Kal, do you ever get

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:07.130
worried that people will get
very upset about these kinds

00:18:07.130 --> 00:18:08.690
of toons and do something
about it?

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:10.740
Because after all, all those
guys that you're complaining

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:13.270
about guns, they've
all got guns.

00:18:13.270 --> 00:18:15.860
And I thought, well, I've
been lucky so far.

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:18.430
I've had cartoonists colleagues
both here and

00:18:18.430 --> 00:18:21.650
abroad who have been
threatened and

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:22.910
this sort of thing.

00:18:22.910 --> 00:18:24.630
But it's not been such
an issue for me.

00:18:24.630 --> 00:18:27.600
But then another Lebanese
cartoonist perked up.

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:29.900
And he said, you know,
here in Lebanon, it's

00:18:29.900 --> 00:18:31.380
the exact same thing.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:34.560
Except everyone here has
got rocket launchers.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:37.820
So it made me feel an awful lot
better, that conversation.

00:18:37.820 --> 00:18:41.190
I didn't feel so under siege.

00:18:41.190 --> 00:18:43.320
Now this cartoon is one about
the financial world.

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:46.450
This is my most popular
cartoon ever.

00:18:46.450 --> 00:18:49.760
It's just a normal day at the
nation's most important

00:18:49.760 --> 00:18:50.880
financial institution.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:52.250
So this little guy there on the
left, he's saying, "I've

00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:55.980
got a stock here that could
really excel." "Really excel?"

00:18:55.980 --> 00:18:58.310
"Excel?" "Sell?" "Sell?" "Sell!"
"Sell!" Sell!" "Sell!"

00:18:58.310 --> 00:18:59.630
"Sell!" "Sell!" "Sell!"

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:00.690
"This is madness.

00:19:00.690 --> 00:19:02.020
I can't take anymore.

00:19:02.020 --> 00:19:05.165
Good bye." "Good bye?" "Bye?"
"Buy?" "Buy?" "Buy?" "Buy?"

00:19:05.165 --> 00:19:08.450
"Buy?" "I've got a stock here
that could really excel."

00:19:08.450 --> 00:19:11.990
So anyway, so this cartoon
appears 1989.

00:19:11.990 --> 00:19:15.540
It appears "Baltimore Sun,"
"New York Times," "Herald

00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:18.720
Tribune." Starts picked up
by other newspapers.

00:19:18.720 --> 00:19:21.400
And the next thing you know,
I'm getting phone calls.

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:26.000
Scores of phone calls
from stockbrokers.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.690
And they're saying two things.

00:19:27.690 --> 00:19:30.700
One, they want a copy
of this cartoon.

00:19:30.700 --> 00:19:34.220
And two, this is exactly
what its like.

00:19:34.220 --> 00:19:36.550
This is what they all say.

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:39.690
And ever since then, on almost a
weekly basis, I get requests

00:19:39.690 --> 00:19:43.890
to use this cartoon in books,
encyclopedias, on mugs.

00:19:43.890 --> 00:19:47.650
I had that request six months
ago from a stockbroker in Hong

00:19:47.650 --> 00:19:50.650
Kong, where we took this
cartoon, they blew it up.

00:19:50.650 --> 00:19:54.470
We divided it and made it one
single line, 24 feet.

00:19:54.470 --> 00:19:57.530
And they put it in the
lobby of their place.

00:19:57.530 --> 00:19:58.650
So it's amazing.

00:19:58.650 --> 00:20:03.670
Some cartoons can really hit a
raw nerve if you get it right.

00:20:03.670 --> 00:20:05.535
And some cartoons, of course,
we're always about trying

00:20:05.535 --> 00:20:07.420
getting things down
to their simplest.

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:11.480
But sometimes, keeping things
complex are also great ways to

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:12.130
tell the story.

00:20:12.130 --> 00:20:15.710
So this is about Obamacare,
navigating US health.

00:20:15.710 --> 00:20:17.790
Before Obamacare, this is
what it looks like.

00:20:17.790 --> 00:20:20.590
And after Obamacare, this is
what it's going to look like.

00:20:20.590 --> 00:20:20.830
.

00:20:20.830 --> 00:20:26.140
So it's a great way of telling
the story in pictures.

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:28.770
So this is kind of what I
thought your relationship to

00:20:28.770 --> 00:20:31.370
China is here, between
Google and China.

00:20:31.370 --> 00:20:33.820
There is nothing more
annoying on the web

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:35.790
than an unwanted pop-up.

00:20:35.790 --> 00:20:38.110
And that's a Chinese dragon kind
of finding its way into

00:20:38.110 --> 00:20:39.410
everything you do here.

00:20:39.410 --> 00:20:42.670
So anyways, for the outside
world, this is what we think

00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:43.800
you guys at Google are like.

00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:45.140
You don't have your shoes on.

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:46.700
You always got a hat on.

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:48.480
And you're always just
tapping away.

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:50.770
So hopefully I'm going
you learn something.

00:20:50.770 --> 00:20:53.010
So the cartoon I do on Google
will be a little bit more

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:54.490
representative.

00:20:54.490 --> 00:20:57.290
So always as cartoonists, we're
always ingesting as much

00:20:57.290 --> 00:21:01.330
information as we can about the
subjects we're covering.

00:21:01.330 --> 00:21:04.740
Now I want to show you a quick
notice about how cartoons have

00:21:04.740 --> 00:21:06.410
progressed over recent years.

00:21:06.410 --> 00:21:09.140
And this is a pre-internet
cartoon I

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:10.110
want to tell you about.

00:21:10.110 --> 00:21:11.710
So the story is this.

00:21:11.710 --> 00:21:14.460
Mikhail Gorbachev is
now the new leader

00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:15.320
of the Soviet Union.

00:21:15.320 --> 00:21:17.930
1986, I think.

00:21:17.930 --> 00:21:19.940
And I was working in
the UK at the time.

00:21:19.940 --> 00:21:22.630
And there was this brand new
show called "Miami Vice." You

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:23.980
guys know that?

00:21:23.980 --> 00:21:26.050
Brand new in 1986.

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:29.890
And I say, wouldn't it be cool
to get this new cool new style

00:21:29.890 --> 00:21:34.140
leader and draw him as the guy
from "Miami Vice." And the

00:21:34.140 --> 00:21:36.610
editors at "The Economist" said,
great, Kal, go for it.

00:21:36.610 --> 00:21:39.110
I had 24 hours to complete
the cover.

00:21:39.110 --> 00:21:43.260
But the bad news was I got home
and I realized I had no

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:46.240
photos of "Miami Vice."

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:48.540
And in those days, if you didn't
have any photos, you

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:49.670
had no photos.

00:21:49.670 --> 00:21:52.270
There was no way to
get anything.

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:55.410
And so I turned to my wife and
I said, well, what are we

00:21:55.410 --> 00:21:55.880
going to do?

00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:57.040
So we said, what do we do?

00:21:57.040 --> 00:21:59.130
The typical thing,
we went shopping.

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:01.770
We went out and bought
some clothes.

00:22:01.770 --> 00:22:07.650
And this is me modeling for
the actual cartoon.

00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:08.850
Of course, that's not my car.

00:22:08.850 --> 00:22:10.080
That's not really my car.

00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:12.650
But those are my clothes that
Mikhail Gorbachev is wearing

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:13.540
in the cartoon.

00:22:13.540 --> 00:22:14.720
So that was pre-internet.

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:17.550
So here's a cartoon
post-internet.

00:22:17.550 --> 00:22:19.140
So the story of this
cartoon took place

00:22:19.140 --> 00:22:20.760
about five years ago.

00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:25.520
I was on vacation in the Big
Horn Mountains of Wyoming,

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:27.060
Northeast Wyoming.

00:22:27.060 --> 00:22:30.190
And I made the mistake
of checking my email.

00:22:30.190 --> 00:22:35.130
There was a note from "The
Economist" saying, , Kal, you

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:37.470
left a sketch for us that we
really liked about the

00:22:37.470 --> 00:22:41.430
over-consumption of
oil between the

00:22:41.430 --> 00:22:42.550
United States and China.

00:22:42.550 --> 00:22:45.030
And would you please paint it.

00:22:45.030 --> 00:22:47.470
We want to put it on the
cover this week.

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:51.130
So I get back to them with a
note and say, guys, there's

00:22:51.130 --> 00:22:52.370
three problems.

00:22:52.370 --> 00:22:54.900
First, I'm on vacation.

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:57.520
Second, I don't have
any paints with me.

00:22:57.520 --> 00:22:59.910
And third, I'm in the
middle of nowhere.

00:22:59.910 --> 00:23:00.150
Right?

00:23:00.150 --> 00:23:02.450
So I figured that kind of
will settle the score.

00:23:02.450 --> 00:23:05.110
But then they get back to me and
say, Kal, see what you can

00:23:05.110 --> 00:23:07.320
do and call us in the morning.

00:23:07.320 --> 00:23:07.920
So I'm going, oh man.

00:23:07.920 --> 00:23:08.210
All right.

00:23:08.210 --> 00:23:11.030
So I'm at a dude range.

00:23:11.030 --> 00:23:13.200
And so, I go talk
to the dudes.

00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:17.210
I go, dudes, where can
I get some paints?

00:23:17.210 --> 00:23:19.410
And they say, well, this
dirt road, 10 miles.

00:23:19.410 --> 00:23:19.910
Go down there.

00:23:19.910 --> 00:23:20.700
There's a pharmacy.

00:23:20.700 --> 00:23:22.610
In the back row of the pharmacy,
there's a lady.

00:23:22.610 --> 00:23:24.120
She likes to paint.

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:25.330
Go talk with her.

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:26.460
Go find the lady.

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:28.010
She gives me a little
kids' pack.

00:23:28.010 --> 00:23:29.376
You know the little six?

00:23:29.376 --> 00:23:30.810
Them round little things?

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:31.480
That's what I got.

00:23:31.480 --> 00:23:32.890
Little six pack of kid paints.

00:23:32.890 --> 00:23:34.830
One piece of watercolor paper.

00:23:34.830 --> 00:23:36.760
And I go back to the kitchen
table of the dude

00:23:36.760 --> 00:23:38.240
ranch, and I do this.

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:40.300
And notice the primary
colors here.

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:42.790
It's very basic colors
in this.

00:23:42.790 --> 00:23:46.060
And then I scan it on my
portable scanner laptop.

00:23:46.060 --> 00:23:48.320
Email it, like dial-up.

00:23:48.320 --> 00:23:50.400
Five hours later, it
arrives in London.

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:52.800
But the key thing was that two
days later, being "The

00:23:52.800 --> 00:23:56.930
Economist," this appeared in
every country around the world

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:58.650
from the mountains of Wyoming.

00:23:58.650 --> 00:24:00.960
And ever since then and actually
before, wherever I am

00:24:00.960 --> 00:24:03.480
in the world, I'm always doing
my cartoons for "The

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:06.850
Economist." And it's
a very easy thing.

00:24:06.850 --> 00:24:09.440
Particularly compared to what
it was when I first started

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:12.800
with "The Economist."
It was 1978.

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:14.110
I worked in UK.

00:24:14.110 --> 00:24:16.270
I came back to Baltimore
to New York in the

00:24:16.270 --> 00:24:18.560
United States in 1988.

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:21.020
And the internet was just
in its early days.

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:24.490
And I pioneered the use of
sending my cartoons to London

00:24:24.490 --> 00:24:25.690
from Baltimore.

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:28.210
But in those days, a 400K
file would take

00:24:28.210 --> 00:24:29.850
three hours to send.

00:24:29.850 --> 00:24:32.070
And now, of course, we could be
anywhere in the world, and

00:24:32.070 --> 00:24:34.510
I could send my cartoon.

00:24:34.510 --> 00:24:37.056
So a lot of people ask
me, all right, how

00:24:37.056 --> 00:24:38.410
do you do your cartoons?

00:24:38.410 --> 00:24:38.660
All right.

00:24:38.660 --> 00:24:42.900
So one thing is that I'm
constantly trying to ingest as

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:46.490
much information as I can from
a whole variety of sources.

00:24:46.490 --> 00:24:49.690
TV, the Web mostly.

00:24:49.690 --> 00:24:51.090
Radios really great.

00:24:51.090 --> 00:24:54.030
And of course, you're reading
some magazines as well.

00:24:54.030 --> 00:24:57.100
But keeping up is
really tough.

00:24:57.100 --> 00:25:01.600
So now, because I consider
myself a columnist, my first

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:04.120
job is being a journalist,
gathering the information.

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:07.970
But now, I have to try to get an
angle on an information and

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:11.080
not find out what's funny today,
but find out what is

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:13.040
important today.

00:25:13.040 --> 00:25:17.250
And once I've got that, now I
have to take that idea and

00:25:17.250 --> 00:25:18.160
turn it into a cartoon.

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:20.390
And in the beginning, it's
awfully difficult.

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:23.560
So what I do is I give
myself lots of paper.

00:25:23.560 --> 00:25:25.080
I put it on my desk.

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:27.870
And I think and draw
at the same time.

00:25:27.870 --> 00:25:30.720
And part of this about the
creativity, you try to fire

00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:33.140
between the two halves of you
brain, the logical and the

00:25:33.140 --> 00:25:36.905
creative, saying what is
interesting and what logically

00:25:36.905 --> 00:25:37.540
would work.

00:25:37.540 --> 00:25:40.070
But then, also what will be cool
and what will be funny.

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:41.410
And I'm doing lots
of sketches.

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:45.380
And my first sketch is often
virtually hieroglyphic.

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:47.340
In fact, let me show you one
of my early sketches for a

00:25:47.340 --> 00:25:48.460
cartoon I did recently.

00:25:48.460 --> 00:25:49.733
Can you see that?

00:25:49.733 --> 00:25:50.640
AUDIENCE: It's a Frank
Gehry design.

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:51.520
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: That's it.

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:51.690
[LAUGHS]

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:52.830
It's a perfect--

00:25:52.830 --> 00:25:55.680
you can see obviously what's
going on here.

00:25:55.680 --> 00:25:57.810
But this was, I was commissioned
to do a cover for

00:25:57.810 --> 00:25:59.400
"The Economist" recently.

00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:03.770
And they wanted me to do
something about raising taxes

00:26:03.770 --> 00:26:05.660
on rich people.

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:07.810
So I started to conjure up what
would be a good idea.

00:26:07.810 --> 00:26:09.850
And I thought, how about
fox hunting?

00:26:09.850 --> 00:26:12.520
That's the kind of thing that
rich people maybe do.

00:26:12.520 --> 00:26:14.710
But I thought I'd give it
a little bit of a twist.

00:26:14.710 --> 00:26:19.230
And instead of having fox
hunters chasing foxes, how

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:22.790
about if I have politicians
chasing rich people?

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.310
And so this was what my first
sketch looked like.

00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:26.210
But the next sketch
is much clearer.

00:26:26.210 --> 00:26:27.250
There you go.

00:26:27.250 --> 00:26:30.840
OK But already, I'm beginning
to map out all the varieties

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:34.120
shapes and trying to conjure
up a composition.

00:26:34.120 --> 00:26:36.680
The next sketch that I do on
top of that is getting a

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:37.590
little bit clearer.

00:26:37.590 --> 00:26:39.860
You might be able to see some
of the characters appearing

00:26:39.860 --> 00:26:43.410
down in the southeast
part of the drawing.

00:26:43.410 --> 00:26:46.910
And the next drawing still is
getting more and more clear.

00:26:46.910 --> 00:26:49.980
And at the same time while I'm
doing this in London, they are

00:26:49.980 --> 00:26:52.150
playing around with the
captions, the titles of the

00:26:52.150 --> 00:26:52.800
publication.

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:55.260
And they're also working on
compositions as well.

00:26:55.260 --> 00:26:57.650
Someone might have something
like this. "Follow the Money."

00:26:57.650 --> 00:27:02.180
Or "Pursue the Rich." I think
we have another one here.

00:27:02.180 --> 00:27:07.380
Next, once we have settled on
the pencil sketch, I now am

00:27:07.380 --> 00:27:09.430
working on the color, including
creating the

00:27:09.430 --> 00:27:11.190
caricatures that are
going to go in it.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:13.990
And here, you can see the
Barack Obama version.

00:27:13.990 --> 00:27:18.720
And finally, when I've painted
it all, it looks like this in

00:27:18.720 --> 00:27:19.850
watercolor.

00:27:19.850 --> 00:27:22.640
And it's quite large
this one, I think.

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:25.790
And this whole process between
this, actually, the original

00:27:25.790 --> 00:27:28.200
sketch that I showed you
and this finished color

00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:31.630
cover, is 36 hours.

00:27:31.630 --> 00:27:34.500
36 hours from that little
sketch and all those

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:35.450
iterations.

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:38.220
So one of the things about being
in my craft is that you

00:27:38.220 --> 00:27:40.370
have to love deadlines.

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:41.610
Not everyone loves a deadline.

00:27:41.610 --> 00:27:43.360
We live on a daily deadlines.

00:27:43.360 --> 00:27:46.640
I mean, we're creating art and
commentary on a deadline.

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:50.270
In fact, I tell people never
go to the pub with a

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:53.720
cartoonist, because we will wait
'til one minute before

00:27:53.720 --> 00:27:57.000
closing time before we offer
to buy you a drink.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:58.440
Because we just love
deadlines.

00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:01.860
It's just the way
that we operate.

00:28:01.860 --> 00:28:03.275
So now a little bit
onto technology.

00:28:03.275 --> 00:28:04.940
I wanted to tell you guys
a little bit about it.

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:08.170
We're always concerned about
what's happening to

00:28:08.170 --> 00:28:10.880
newspapers, because it's the
natural home of cartoonists.

00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:16.050
But my senior thesis at
University back in 1977 was a

00:28:16.050 --> 00:28:20.350
13 minute long animated cartoon,
back in the old day,

00:28:20.350 --> 00:28:23.920
when you had to hand draw cells
after cell after cell.

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:26.950
And the first thing I want to
show you here is that I've

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:30.690
been an artist in residence at
UNBC, which is a university

00:28:30.690 --> 00:28:31.610
near Baltimore.

00:28:31.610 --> 00:28:35.340
And I've been exploring some
cool stuff in animation.

00:28:35.340 --> 00:28:36.750
But I'm going to start
off with this--

00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:38.540
there's going to be a 30 second
television commercial

00:28:38.540 --> 00:28:39.840
I'm going to show you here.

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:41.075
It aired in 1986.

00:28:41.075 --> 00:28:44.110
It won several international
animation awards.

00:28:44.110 --> 00:28:47.550
It was done with the help of
Richard Williams, who's the

00:28:47.550 --> 00:28:51.030
animation director for "Who
Framed Roger Rabbit" and won

00:28:51.030 --> 00:28:52.390
several other awards.

00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:57.400
And it stars Margaret Thatcher
and Neil Kinnock, who was the

00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:58.808
Labour-- at the time.

00:28:58.808 --> 00:28:59.776
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:28:59.776 --> 00:29:02.438
-Did you consider that some
newspapers treat politics with

00:29:02.438 --> 00:29:04.132
a trace of bias?

00:29:04.132 --> 00:29:06.120
One side always right.

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:11.020
The other side, always wrong.

00:29:11.020 --> 00:29:14.940
Or the other way around.

00:29:14.940 --> 00:29:17.656
Today, we'll show all
politicians without bias-- not

00:29:17.656 --> 00:29:21.838
as saints or devils, but
ordinary people.

00:29:21.838 --> 00:29:22.330
-Hi-ya!

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:23.806
-Order!

00:29:23.806 --> 00:29:24.790
-Order!

00:29:24.790 --> 00:29:26.040
-Oh!

00:29:29.240 --> 00:29:31.480
-"Today" covers the newspaper,
not the news.

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:34.952
"Today," the newspaper that's
broken the mold.

00:29:34.952 --> 00:29:35.940
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:29:35.940 --> 00:29:36.100
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: All right.

00:29:36.100 --> 00:29:36.600
Give it up for that cartoon.

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:38.380
Isn't that awesome?

00:29:38.380 --> 00:29:39.910
That is so cool.

00:29:39.910 --> 00:29:41.370
So that was really great.

00:29:41.370 --> 00:29:43.170
I get a kick out
of seeing that.

00:29:43.170 --> 00:29:45.190
I've seen it so many-- it's just
really beautifully done.

00:29:45.190 --> 00:29:45.900
It's really funny.

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:47.020
It's smart.

00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:49.120
And so you see something like
this that excited me about the

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:51.700
prospect of saying, wouldn't
be great to make political

00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:53.730
cartoons come alive?

00:29:53.730 --> 00:29:54.980
Wouldn't that be awesome?

00:29:54.980 --> 00:29:56.770
But in those days, it was a
problem, because this took

00:29:56.770 --> 00:29:59.990
three months to make 700-some
odd drawings.

00:29:59.990 --> 00:30:04.360
And the prospect of being able
to do something about news,

00:30:04.360 --> 00:30:07.970
when news changes like this, but
animation was so slow, it

00:30:07.970 --> 00:30:09.330
didn't seem possible.

00:30:09.330 --> 00:30:12.750
Today, of course, new
technologies are allowing more

00:30:12.750 --> 00:30:15.820
prospects and more possibilities
for animation to

00:30:15.820 --> 00:30:16.780
become King.

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:19.290
And I'm extremely excited
about the possibilities.

00:30:19.290 --> 00:30:21.540
I'm just going to share with
you just that one little

00:30:21.540 --> 00:30:22.400
project that--

00:30:22.400 --> 00:30:24.400
actually, a couple little
projects I did.

00:30:24.400 --> 00:30:29.350
Back in the 2008 election cycle,
I worked with Second

00:30:29.350 --> 00:30:32.000
City, the improv comedy troupe,
and did a nationwide

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:33.710
show with them.

00:30:33.710 --> 00:30:37.740
But as part of it, I had built
a few life-size versions of

00:30:37.740 --> 00:30:39.990
some of my caricatures,
including this one of George

00:30:39.990 --> 00:30:42.660
Bush, and then turned them into
digital characters, like

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:44.730
a digital Hillary Clinton.

00:30:44.730 --> 00:30:48.110
And I did a John McCain.

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:52.020
And as part of the my show, I
would do a live bit, where I

00:30:52.020 --> 00:30:56.030
call live animation, where I
would be backstage in motion

00:30:56.030 --> 00:31:00.220
capture suit with voice
recognition software on a mic.

00:31:00.220 --> 00:31:03.190
And my character, let's say John
McCain, would appear on

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:04.490
the screen in front
of an audience.

00:31:04.490 --> 00:31:07.030
We actually did a show at the
Yerba Buena Art Center here.

00:31:07.030 --> 00:31:08.800
Packed house.

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:11.730
And we would have a live press
conference between the

00:31:11.730 --> 00:31:14.730
audience and the cartoon
characters.

00:31:14.730 --> 00:31:16.830
But for the Yerba Buena show,
which was really fun, we

00:31:16.830 --> 00:31:20.150
actually did a dance off between
Barack Obama and John

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:23.250
McCain, whereby we would select
different dance styles

00:31:23.250 --> 00:31:24.120
from the audience.

00:31:24.120 --> 00:31:28.400
And then I would have to dance
as these characters to music.

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:30.810
And then the audience would vote
to see who would get a

00:31:30.810 --> 00:31:32.130
certain amount of
electoral votes.

00:31:32.130 --> 00:31:33.490
It was really kind of cool.

00:31:33.490 --> 00:31:36.890
The last shows we did were in
New York City in Times Square.

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:39.820
We had a debate, actually,
between these two guys.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:42.780
And I would actually do a
personal interview with them

00:31:42.780 --> 00:31:43.590
during the debate.

00:31:43.590 --> 00:31:45.660
In fact, I'm going to do one
right now with John McCain

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:46.700
here, Senator McCain.

00:31:46.700 --> 00:31:49.380
You had Sarah Palin
as your candidate.

00:31:49.380 --> 00:31:52.630
Do you really believe that she
was qualified to be president?

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:53.482
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:31:53.482 --> 00:31:55.490
-Listen, my friends.

00:31:55.490 --> 00:31:59.830
Sarah Palin is qualified
to be president.

00:31:59.830 --> 00:32:06.240
She has ridden caribou to hunt
polar bears with bazookas.

00:32:06.240 --> 00:32:12.350
She has caught Chinook salmon
blindfolded with her teeth.

00:32:12.350 --> 00:32:17.304
No community organizer in
Chicago has ever done that.

00:32:17.304 --> 00:32:17.781
Right?

00:32:17.781 --> 00:32:18.260
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:32:18.260 --> 00:32:18.620
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: That's right.

00:32:18.620 --> 00:32:18.950
Thank you.

00:32:18.950 --> 00:32:20.230
Give it up for Senator McCain.

00:32:20.230 --> 00:32:21.120
Thank you very much, Senator.

00:32:21.120 --> 00:32:22.510
Thank you very much
for coming.

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:23.660
That's really great.

00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:26.750
So in addition to doing these
3D cartoons, I've also now

00:32:26.750 --> 00:32:30.130
been doing some 2D stuff as
well, including two cartoons

00:32:30.130 --> 00:32:31.010
I'm going to show you here.

00:32:31.010 --> 00:32:33.500
About a minute and a half each,
commissioned by "The

00:32:33.500 --> 00:32:36.868
Economist" on economic terms.

00:32:36.868 --> 00:32:39.288
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:32:39.288 --> 00:32:42.192
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

00:32:42.192 --> 00:32:45.590
-When the price of an asset
rises faster than can be

00:32:45.590 --> 00:32:48.140
explained by economic
fundamentals,

00:32:48.140 --> 00:32:50.203
it creates a bubble.

00:32:50.203 --> 00:32:51.415
[POP]

00:32:51.415 --> 00:32:51.700
[CRASH]

00:32:51.700 --> 00:32:54.950
-And those bubbles include tulip
mania in Holland during

00:32:54.950 --> 00:32:58.625
the 17th century, when the
prices of tulips reached

00:32:58.625 --> 00:33:00.080
unbearable levels.

00:33:00.080 --> 00:33:04.200
And South Sea bubble in Britain
a century later.

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:07.360
Here, speculators, which
included a vast array of

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:10.890
citizens, including
parliamentarians and a king's

00:33:10.890 --> 00:33:14.550
mistress drove up the share
price of the South Sea Trading

00:33:14.550 --> 00:33:17.763
Company with disastrous
results.

00:33:17.763 --> 00:33:18.470
[POP]

00:33:18.470 --> 00:33:19.120
[CRASH]

00:33:19.120 --> 00:33:22.970
-There have been many others
since, including the dot-com

00:33:22.970 --> 00:33:25.970
bubble in internet company
shares that burst in 2000.

00:33:25.970 --> 00:33:26.470
[POP]

00:33:26.470 --> 00:33:30.804
-And the bubble in house prices,
which when it burst in

00:33:30.804 --> 00:33:33.648
2007, helped to trigger
the recent

00:33:33.648 --> 00:33:34.596
political economic downturn.

00:33:34.596 --> 00:33:36.018
[POP]

00:33:36.018 --> 00:33:37.450
[CRASH]

00:33:37.450 --> 00:33:39.850
-Economists argued whether
bubbles are caused by the

00:33:39.850 --> 00:33:43.690
irrational behavior of crowds,
aided in part by savvy

00:33:43.690 --> 00:33:49.000
speculators, or are the result
of misinformed consumers who

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:52.560
assume the inflated prices
are sensible.

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:57.830
Whatever their cause, bubbles do
not last forever, and often

00:33:57.830 --> 00:34:02.734
end not with a pop,
but with a crash.

00:34:02.734 --> 00:34:05.550
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:34:05.550 --> 00:34:06.230
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: There we go.

00:34:06.230 --> 00:34:07.910
All right.

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:08.889
We've got another
one coming here.

00:34:08.889 --> 00:34:10.810
One more to show you.

00:34:10.810 --> 00:34:19.810
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

