want to deliver something that

00:45:58.530 --> 00:46:00.690
has all those layers
to it, if you like.

00:46:00.690 --> 00:46:03.830
Partly, I do it as an
honor to my reader.

00:46:03.830 --> 00:46:07.260
I feel that if you feel like
I'm investing in you, then

00:46:07.260 --> 00:46:09.490
you're going to reward me by
spending two or three more

00:46:09.490 --> 00:46:10.700
seconds with the cartoon.

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:12.680
And then it gives you the
opportunity to create a

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:14.790
relationship over time.

00:46:14.790 --> 00:46:17.980
In fact, I like to say every
cartoon is a sentence.

00:46:17.980 --> 00:46:20.030
And a week is a paragraph.

00:46:20.030 --> 00:46:22.750
And then over time, we're having
a long conversation

00:46:22.750 --> 00:46:25.660
that we have to carry on
for decades, hopefully.

00:46:25.660 --> 00:46:28.900
And the idea, however, is that,
for any conversation, is

00:46:28.900 --> 00:46:30.780
you want to keep
it interesting.

00:46:30.780 --> 00:46:32.400
And the way to keep it
interesting is you want to

00:46:32.400 --> 00:46:33.790
have variety in it.

00:46:33.790 --> 00:46:35.390
Some of my cartoons
are serious,

00:46:35.390 --> 00:46:36.520
some of them are funny.

00:46:36.520 --> 00:46:38.100
Some of them have caricatures.

00:46:38.100 --> 00:46:39.630
Some have symbols in them.

00:46:39.630 --> 00:46:41.845
I've used all these different
tools in order to keep it, so

00:46:41.845 --> 00:46:43.870
every time you open the cartoon,
the newspaper, the

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:46.200
magazine, you don't know what
you're going to get.

00:46:46.200 --> 00:46:50.870
So I start the day, usually say,
up 'til 10 or 11 o'clock

00:46:50.870 --> 00:46:52.560
cogitating the news.

00:46:52.560 --> 00:46:54.780
Now, of course, I'm constantly
cogitating the news.

00:46:54.780 --> 00:46:56.690
Constantly ingesting
information.

00:46:56.690 --> 00:46:59.100
Listening and trying to
come up with ideas.

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:01.320
And I never come up with
ideas ahead of time.

00:47:01.320 --> 00:47:03.720
You're always working on that
day, because there's always

00:47:03.720 --> 00:47:05.280
news that changing
and breaking.

00:47:05.280 --> 00:47:07.220
I don't have anything
in reserve.

00:47:07.220 --> 00:47:09.810
And so by about midday,
I should have

00:47:09.810 --> 00:47:11.300
settled down on my idea.

00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:15.090
I spent three hours then doing
the pencil sketch, refining

00:47:15.090 --> 00:47:17.840
like I did with that cover you
saw, getting everything right.

00:47:17.840 --> 00:47:20.220
I then let the editors
know, here's what the

00:47:20.220 --> 00:47:21.070
I'm thinking of doing.

00:47:21.070 --> 00:47:22.550
We get it signed off on.

00:47:22.550 --> 00:47:25.080
And then it takes me three
hours to apply

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:26.730
the ink to the drawing.

00:47:26.730 --> 00:47:29.770
I'm using an old-fashioned quill
pen and a bottle of ink.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:31.330
Scratch, scratch, scratch.

00:47:31.330 --> 00:47:31.640
Think.

00:47:31.640 --> 00:47:32.420
Scratch, scratch, scratch.

00:47:32.420 --> 00:47:33.600
Headphones on.

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:36.980
It's a wonderful experience.

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:41.600
And then maybe by 6 o'clock,
7 o'clock, I might have the

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:42.150
thing completed.

00:47:42.150 --> 00:47:42.830
So, it takes that long.

00:47:42.830 --> 00:47:45.220
And then, you add color to
it, it can be longer.

00:47:45.220 --> 00:47:49.120
But all this experience is is
that every cartoon you do is a

00:47:49.120 --> 00:47:52.100
practice for the next cartoon
you're going to do.

00:47:52.100 --> 00:47:54.300
Because when you work
on a deadline, you

00:47:54.300 --> 00:47:56.000
never finish the cartoon.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:57.230
You have to stop it.

00:47:57.230 --> 00:48:00.080
If you wanted to finish, you'd
need another five, or six, or

00:48:00.080 --> 00:48:02.300
seven hours to get it the
way you want it to.

00:48:02.300 --> 00:48:03.360
But you have to stop.

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:05.770
And at that point, you
learn the lessons.

00:48:05.770 --> 00:48:07.740
And then you apply them
to the next one.

00:48:07.740 --> 00:48:10.140
And it's part of the reason what
I love about my craft, is

00:48:10.140 --> 00:48:12.560
that I feel that a decade from
now, two years from now, I'll

00:48:12.560 --> 00:48:15.350
be better than I am today,
because you're constantly

00:48:15.350 --> 00:48:17.750
learning and building
on your experiences.

00:48:17.750 --> 00:48:21.370
AUDIENCE: I remember the cartoon
you did for 9/11.

00:48:21.370 --> 00:48:25.780
And I also remember the
controversy over the headline

00:48:25.780 --> 00:48:28.740
that "The Onion" printed in the
same time period, which

00:48:28.740 --> 00:48:32.310
was perhaps very insightful,
but also quite irreverent.

00:48:32.310 --> 00:48:34.860
And I was just wondering, there
is an irreverence that

00:48:34.860 --> 00:48:36.500
you draw with about
political leaders.

00:48:36.500 --> 00:48:38.580
And I'm just trying to figure
out the line that you draw in

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:42.280
terms of what subject matter for
education, versus subject

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:44.105
matter for satire, versus
subject matter for

00:48:44.105 --> 00:48:44.810
irreverence.

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:45.335
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: Yeah.

00:48:45.335 --> 00:48:47.220
That's such a great question,
because this is

00:48:47.220 --> 00:48:49.345
thing about the line.

00:48:49.345 --> 00:48:52.180
First of all, I've travelled
the world representing the

00:48:52.180 --> 00:48:54.150
United States and the State
Department, speaking of

00:48:54.150 --> 00:48:57.240
freedom of expression in a
whole array of countries.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:00.090
And that question is asked
to me all the time.

00:49:00.090 --> 00:49:04.100
And as I reflect, I realize
that I ask myself that

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:05.420
question every day.

00:49:05.420 --> 00:49:07.900
Whenever I'm doing a cartoon,
you're assessing who your

00:49:07.900 --> 00:49:09.670
audience is.

00:49:09.670 --> 00:49:13.750
How are you going to try to be
able sometimes push the line

00:49:13.750 --> 00:49:16.250
on the cartoon, or get a
point across without

00:49:16.250 --> 00:49:17.510
going over the line?

00:49:17.510 --> 00:49:20.640
And one of the things is that
the line is constantly moving.

00:49:20.640 --> 00:49:23.430
And where it was yesterday
is not going to

00:49:23.430 --> 00:49:24.190
be where it is today.

00:49:24.190 --> 00:49:26.300
In every country, every culture,
they've all got

00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:27.730
different places.

00:49:27.730 --> 00:49:30.470
And when our cartoonists get
together, we're in that

00:49:30.470 --> 00:49:31.135
situation too.

00:49:31.135 --> 00:49:33.460
And we've had situations where
almost all of us have gone

00:49:33.460 --> 00:49:36.670
over the line, either
deliberately or by

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:38.820
mistake over time.

00:49:38.820 --> 00:49:42.410
And so, it is something that
you have to be very, very

00:49:42.410 --> 00:49:42.890
careful with.

00:49:42.890 --> 00:49:46.000
Now part of the thing about my
work is that my cartoons are

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:47.270
very detailed.

00:49:47.270 --> 00:49:51.310
And so one of the things that
I definitely try to do with

00:49:51.310 --> 00:49:55.420
all the freedom that I have
is to be very responsible.

00:49:55.420 --> 00:49:57.530
So I want to make sure I'm not
doing cartoons that could be

00:49:57.530 --> 00:50:00.660
deemed to be racist or sexist.

00:50:00.660 --> 00:50:03.670
I feel that I can cover any
subject that I want, but it's

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:05.760
how you cover the subject
inevitably that

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:07.370
gets you into trouble.

00:50:07.370 --> 00:50:10.290
And so even if I wanted to do
something about the Prophet

00:50:10.290 --> 00:50:13.590
Muhammad, I could probably do
a cartoon on that subject.

00:50:13.590 --> 00:50:16.910
But maybe opt now to draw the
Prophet, because I know that

00:50:16.910 --> 00:50:19.470
the outrage that it would create
and people would lose

00:50:19.470 --> 00:50:21.700
track of the point that
I wanted to make.

00:50:21.700 --> 00:50:24.320
Because at the end of the day,
I want to be an effective

00:50:24.320 --> 00:50:25.540
commentator.

00:50:25.540 --> 00:50:26.890
I want to get a point across.

00:50:26.890 --> 00:50:28.820
And I want to engage
the opposition.

00:50:28.820 --> 00:50:31.930
I don't want to be speaking
to the converted.

00:50:31.930 --> 00:50:34.050
And so in order to do that, you
have to realize that you

00:50:34.050 --> 00:50:36.600
can't step so much on the toes
of those people you disagree

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:38.100
with that they stop listening.

00:50:38.100 --> 00:50:40.110
Otherwise, what's the point?

00:50:40.110 --> 00:50:43.020
Because at the end of the day,
I feel like we're kind of an

00:50:43.020 --> 00:50:44.440
instrument of democracy.

00:50:44.440 --> 00:50:47.460
We're trying to get a
conversation going using these

00:50:47.460 --> 00:50:50.980
little pricks, these little
incitements, I guess, where

00:50:50.980 --> 00:50:54.240
cartoon get do to the brain
firing a little bit.

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:57.140
But having said that, there's
always somebody ticked off

00:50:57.140 --> 00:50:58.430
with your cartoons.

00:50:58.430 --> 00:51:00.850
So when I worked in the UK, I
worked in addition to "The

00:51:00.850 --> 00:51:02.580
Economist" from other
newspapers.

00:51:02.580 --> 00:51:04.470
In the UK, you have a situation
where you have about

00:51:04.470 --> 00:51:07.880
a dozen daily newspapers, and
each one is targeted to a

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:10.990
special socioeconomic
demographic.

00:51:10.990 --> 00:51:14.300
Down market, left wing, up
market, right wing, and

00:51:14.300 --> 00:51:16.130
everything in between.

00:51:16.130 --> 00:51:19.120
Here in the US, we have one
newspaper per market usually.

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:22.740
And which means it's read by
everybody in all the different

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:23.570
demographics.

00:51:23.570 --> 00:51:26.430
So every cartoon you do is
ticking somebody off.

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:29.030
And believe me, they
let you know.

00:51:29.030 --> 00:51:32.980
About 85% of my contact with
the public is negative,

00:51:32.980 --> 00:51:34.730
because we deal with ridicule.

00:51:34.730 --> 00:51:36.010
We're making fun of people.

00:51:36.010 --> 00:51:37.380
We're making fun of
the point of view.

00:51:37.380 --> 00:51:40.000
And they get upset, and
they let us know.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:43.020
And so as a result,
you can't help it.

00:51:43.020 --> 00:51:46.270
But the question is, is are you
still being fair within

00:51:46.270 --> 00:51:47.370
that realm?

00:51:47.370 --> 00:51:48.470
And it's a tricky area.

00:51:48.470 --> 00:51:51.840
But believe me, we're thinking
about this all the time.

00:51:51.840 --> 00:51:54.750
Then add the fact that our
audience is now global.

00:51:54.750 --> 00:51:56.610
I can do a cartoon here.

00:51:56.610 --> 00:51:59.790
And then, it could be
willfully misread or

00:51:59.790 --> 00:52:02.230
misrepresented in
another culture.

00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:04.260
And then, you could have
all sorts of problems.

00:52:04.260 --> 00:52:07.750
So it's a really interesting
time.

00:52:07.750 --> 00:52:11.160
Seriously, interesting time to
be doing what we're doing.

00:52:11.160 --> 00:52:15.040
AUDIENCE: Did that problem start
after the internet, or

00:52:15.040 --> 00:52:18.800
was it there before when "The
Economist" was just in print?

00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:20.790
KEVIN KALLAUGHER: Well,
yes. "The Economist"--

00:52:20.790 --> 00:52:22.985
because in some ways, if you
imagine, "The Economist" was

00:52:22.985 --> 00:52:25.690
like the internet before,
because it was one of the only

00:52:25.690 --> 00:52:28.680
global publications.

00:52:28.680 --> 00:52:30.420
And so it was read everywhere.

00:52:30.420 --> 00:52:32.500
And yeah, we would have
situations where, for example,

00:52:32.500 --> 00:52:34.645
I did a cartoon of
Indira Gandhi.

00:52:34.645 --> 00:52:35.900
It appeared on the cover.

00:52:35.900 --> 00:52:37.070
It arrives in India.

00:52:37.070 --> 00:52:37.710
They see it.

00:52:37.710 --> 00:52:38.310
Don't like it.

00:52:38.310 --> 00:52:42.120
They confiscate it and burn all
the copies immediately.

00:52:42.120 --> 00:52:46.140
In Singapore, even to today,
they'll go in and they will

00:52:46.140 --> 00:52:48.110
cut out articles.

00:52:48.110 --> 00:52:51.500
There was a time, I think it
was Singapore, where every

00:52:51.500 --> 00:52:54.990
night, every single individual
magazine that went in would be

00:52:54.990 --> 00:52:56.590
individually censored.

00:52:56.590 --> 00:52:58.060
This article would
be blacked out.

00:52:58.060 --> 00:53:00.090
This picture would be cut out.

00:53:00.090 --> 00:53:02.260
And there's still some
countries where

00:53:02.260 --> 00:53:03.370
that happens today.

00:53:03.370 --> 00:53:06.430
And also, even "The Economist"
will do a cover.

00:53:06.430 --> 00:53:07.840
Now some of "The Economist"
covers can be

00:53:07.840 --> 00:53:08.770
a little bit edgy.

00:53:08.770 --> 00:53:11.840
And it will be well-understood
in certain parts of the world,

00:53:11.840 --> 00:53:14.410
and not understood at all in
other parts of the world.

00:53:14.410 --> 00:53:16.630
And you can also imagine too
that now with "The Economist,"

00:53:16.630 --> 00:53:20.250
we get comments online.

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:24.860
If we some sort of major article
about China, Russia,

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:29.000
Iran, and I think there may be
one other country, they have a

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:34.185
legion of government-paid trolls
who just go out there

00:53:34.185 --> 00:53:39.120
and bombard you with all of
their opinions and so on.

00:53:39.120 --> 00:53:43.415
So you're going to get reaction
when you're global

00:53:43.415 --> 00:53:45.480
with anything, I guess.

00:53:45.480 --> 00:53:46.370
Well, good.

